By SUSAN SALTER REYNOLDS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE FOLLOWING STORY by Cees Nooteboom, translated by Ina Rilke (Harcourt Brace 
& Company: $14.95; 115 pp.) Here is a disturbing fable about a man, nicknamed 
Socrates by his students and colleagues, with a single defining memory, a 
single event in which he came close to living as he ought to have lived; the 
catalyst, a woman."She had shown me a garden that had been closed to me. I was 
still shut out, but at least I had caught a glimpse of it. Glimpse is the wrong 
word. I had heard it. She had made a sound that did not belong to the world. . 
. . Where that sound came from it must be impossible to live." This woman is 
married to a man who doesn't love her. To get revenge, she gives Socrates a 
moment in his life that becomes the eye of the hurricane; he can never get out 
of it. "It was not my soul that would set out on a journey . . . it was my body 
that would embark on endless wanderings, never to be ousted from the universe." 
He tells the story again and again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
