<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'RUBY IN PARADISE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Victor Nunez's 1993 release, one of last year's best, is an intimate, low-key 
film as endearing and staunch as its heroine.A warm, perceptive depiction of 
everyday life, "Ruby" illuminates the inner being of a seemingly ordinary young 
woman in the process of creating a life for herself. It reveals the courage it 
can take to strike out on one's own and to take charge of one's own destiny. It 
marks the screen debut of radiant Ashley Judd (pictured), and features Dorothy 
Lyman as her first employer, Bentley Mitchum as Lyman's memorably nasty son and 
Todd Field as a pivotal man in Judd's life (Cinemax Friday at 8 p.m.). Kevin 
Thomas 
</P>
