<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: CENTRAL: DOWNTOWN; $500,000 MORE OKD FOR CABLE CAR PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOMMY LI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has approved a proposal to increase from $1 million to $1.5 
million the design costs for restoration of Angels Flight, the twin cable-car 
system that once serviced Bunker Hill. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials had originally agreed to pay Harris & Associates $1 million to 
manage reconstruction of Angels Flight, built in 1901 and dismantled in 1969 to 
make way for redevelopment. 
</P>
<P>
 The $537,000 increase mainly arose out of the city's decision to provide 
wheelchair access on one of the cable cars -- even though the city's historic 
railway is exempt from federal Americans with Disabilities Act guidelines, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Council members on Wednesday unanimously approved the added expense to Harris' 
contract, on the condition that an audit be done and that the Community 
Redevelopment Agency seek additional funding from the Metropolitan 
Transportation Authority. 
</P>
<P>
 The council's action also allows the Community Redevelopment Agency board to 
vote on a construction contract later this month, said Jeffrey Skorneck, Bunker 
Hill project manager for the agency. 
</P>
<P>
 Construction could then begin by December, and Angels Flight could be back on 
track by the end of 1995, Skorneck said. 
</P>
<P>
 Dubbed "the world's shortest railway," the restored orange-and-black rail cars 
will run on tracks half a block south of 3rd Street, between Hill and Olive 
streets. TOMMY LI 
</P>
</TEXT>
